Abstract \textbackslash  Electrochemical water splitting for hydrogen generation is a vital part for the prospect of future energy \textbackslash  systems, however, the practical utilization relies on the development of highly active and earth-abundant \textbackslash  catalysts to boost the energy conversion efficiency as well as reduce the cost. Molybdenum diselenide \textbackslash  (MoSe2) is a promising nonprecious metal-based electrocatalyst for hydrogen evolution reaction (HER) in \textbackslash  acidic media, but it exhibits inferior alkaline HER kinetics in great part due to the sluggish water \textbackslash  adsorption/dissociation process. Herein, the alkaline HER kinetics of MoSe2 is substantially accelerated \textbackslash  by heteroatom doping with transition metal ions. Specifically, the Ni-doped MoSe2 nanosheets exhibit the \textbackslash  most impressive catalytic activity in terms of lower overpotential and larger exchange current density. The \textbackslash  density functional theory (DFT) calculation results reveal that Ni/Co doping plays a key role in facilitating \textbackslash  water adsorption as well as optimizing hydrogen adsorption. The present work paves a new way to the \textbackslash  development of low-cost and efficient electrocatalysts towards alkaline HER.

