In this work, nickel molybdate $\left(\mathrm{NiMoO}_{4}\right)$ with a flower-like nanostructure composed of nanosheets was synthesized via a hydrothermal process followed by annealing in air and were evaluated as OER catalysts in $1 \mathrm{M} \mathrm{KOH}$. The dependence of $\mathrm{Fe}$ doping on the catalytic activity of $\mathrm{NiMoO}_{4}$ was studied, and the results demonstrate that $\mathrm{Fe}$ doping can significantly promote the OER kinetics. Detailed electrochemical tests prove that the $\mathrm{Fe}-$ doping-induced synergistic effect should be responsible for the performance improvement. Besides, the real active centers in $\mathrm{Fe}$-doped $\mathrm{NiMoO}_{4}$ were also investigated.

\section{Results and Discussion}
The Fe-doped $\mathrm{NiMoO}_{4}\left(\mathrm{Ni}_{1-\mathrm{x}} \mathrm{Fe}_{\mathrm{x}} \mathrm{MoO}_{4}, \mathrm{x}=0,0.05,0.1\right.$ and 0.2) were synthesized via a hydrothermal process followed by annealing at $500{ }^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$ in air. The crystal phase of $\mathrm{Ni}_{1-\mathrm{x}} \mathrm{Fe}_{\mathrm{x}} \mathrm{MoO}_{4}$ was confirmed by X-ray diffraction (XRD) patterns (Figure 1a), and the results reveal the formation of $\beta-\mathrm{NiMoO}_{4}$ (JCPDS No. $45-0142) .{ }^{[8]}$ No characteristic diffraction peaks of iron oxidebased phases are observed, implying the successful doping of $\mathrm{Fe}$ atoms into $\mathrm{NiMoO}_{4}$ lattice. However, it should be noted that the relative density of (220) peak at $26.6^{\circ}$ decrease with increasing $\mathrm{Fe}$ content. It can be explained that, $\mathrm{Fe}-\mathrm{O}$ bond distance is shorter than $\mathrm{Ni}-\mathrm{O}$ bond distance, and thus the $\mathrm{NiMoO}_{4}$ lattice structure is changed when $\mathrm{Ni}$ atoms are partially replaced by $\mathrm{Fe}$ atoms. ${ }^{[9]}$

