The turnover frequency (TOF) was further calculated to evaluate the intrinsic OER catalytic activities of $\mathrm{Ni}_{0.9} \mathrm{Fe}_{0.1} \mathrm{MoO}_{4}$ and $\mathrm{NiMoO}_{4}$. As shown in Table 1, the TOF of $\mathrm{Ni}_{0.9} \mathrm{Fe}_{0.1} \mathrm{MoO}_{4}$ is $0.032 \mathrm{~s}^{-1}$ at the overpotential of $300 \mathrm{mV}$, which is almost six folds higher than that of $\mathrm{NiMoO}_{4}\left(0.0042 \mathrm{~s}^{-1}\right)$. The result further confirms the enhanced intrinsic activity induced by $\mathrm{Fe}$ doping. It has to be mentioned that, compared with most Ni-based catalysts such as $\mathrm{NiO}$ or $\mathrm{Ni}(\mathrm{OH})_{2}$, the proportion of $\mathrm{Ni}$ content is much lower in $\mathrm{Ni}_{0.9} \mathrm{Fe}_{0.1} \mathrm{MoO}_{4}$, but it deliveres simialr and even better mass activity than $\mathrm{NiO}^{[23]}$. Thus, it can be inferred that, in addition to the oxidation state of $\mathrm{Ni}$, the coordination environment of $\mathrm{Ni}$ might also determine the intrinsic activity of $\mathrm{Ni}$ active sites.

\section{Conclusions}
In summary, $\mathrm{NiMoO}_{4}$-based catalysts were synthesized and evaluated for alkaline OER, and the OER kinetics was substantially enhanced by $\mathrm{Fe}$ doping. The optimal $\mathrm{Ni}_{0.9} \mathrm{Fe}_{0.1} \mathrm{MoO}_{4}$ exhibited a lower overpotential of $299 \mathrm{mV}$ than $\mathrm{NiMoO}_{4}(364 \mathrm{mV})$ at a current density of $10 \mathrm{~mA} \mathrm{~cm}$. $\mathrm{Ni}$ species are demonstrated to be the real active sites, and $\mathrm{NiOOH} / \mathrm{NiO}$ were formed in situ during OER. This work demonstrates $\mathrm{Fe}$ doping is also an effective strategy for improving the catalytic activity of $\mathrm{NiMoO}_{4}$-based catalysts besides $\mathrm{NiO}$ and $\mathrm{Ni}(\mathrm{OH})_{2}$.

