All the chemicals were purchased from Sigma-Aldrich (A.R grade) and used as received without further purification.

Synthesis of $\mathrm{NiMoO}_{4}$ and $\mathrm{Ni}_{1-\mathrm{x}} \mathrm{Fe}_{x} \mathrm{MoO}_{4}$

$\mathrm{NiMoO}_{4}$ were synthesized via a typical hydrothermal treatment followed by annealing process. $1 \mathrm{mmol}$ of $\mathrm{Ni}\left(\mathrm{NO}_{3}\right)_{2} \cdot 6 \mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}$ and $1 \mathrm{mmol}$ of $\mathrm{Na}_{2} \mathrm{MoO}_{4} \cdot 2 \mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}$ were dissolved in $30 \mathrm{~mL}$ deionized (DI) water with vigorous stirring. Next, $0.24 \mathrm{~g}$ urea was added into the solution. After stirring for $30 \mathrm{~min}$, the final solution was transferred to a $45 \mathrm{~mL}$ Teflon lined stainless steel autoclave and kept at $160{ }^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$ for $8 \mathrm{~h}$. Fe-doped $\mathrm{NiMoO}_{4}$ was prepared via the similar procedure by altering the molar ratio of $\mathrm{Ni}\left(\mathrm{NO}_{3}\right)_{2} \cdot 6 \mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}$ to $\mathrm{Fe}\left(\mathrm{NO}_{3}\right)_{3} \cdot 9 \mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}$. For $\mathrm{Ni}_{0.9} \mathrm{Fe}_{0.1} \mathrm{MoO}_{4}, 0.1 \mathrm{mmol}$ $\mathrm{Fe}\left(\mathrm{NO}_{3}\right)_{3} \cdot 9 \mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}$ and $0.9 \mathrm{mmol} \mathrm{Ni}\left(\mathrm{NO}_{3}\right)_{2} \cdot 6 \mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}$ were added in the precursor solution. After the autoclaves were cooled down, the precursor samples were washed with DI water and ethanol three times and dried at $65^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$ for $10 \mathrm{~h}$. Finally, the products were kept at $500^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$ in air for $2 \mathrm{~h}$ to obtain $\mathrm{NiMoO}_{4}$ and $\mathrm{Ni}_{1-x} \mathrm{Fe}_{x} \mathrm{MoO}_{4}$.

\section{Characterization of materials}
The X-ray diffraction (XRD) was performed using Mac Science XRD $(\lambda=$ $1.5406 \AA, 25 \mathrm{~mA}, 40 \mathrm{kV}, 1^{\circ} \mathrm{min}^{-1}$ from 20 to $\left.80^{\circ}\right)$. XPS measurements were carried out on a Phoibos 100 analyzer, using monochrome $\mathrm{Al} \mathrm{K \alpha}$ (hv=1486.6 eV) as the X-ray excitation source. The sample morphologies were recorded by the field emission scanning electron microscope (SEM, JEOL JSM-7500FA, $10 \mathrm{kV}$ ) and transmission electron microscopy (TEM, JEOL JEM-2010, $200 \mathrm{kV}$ ). The specific surface areas of the samples were measured by a TriStar II 3020-BET/BJH analyzer.

Electrochemical Measurements The electrochemical performance were tested by rotating disk electrode system (Pine Instruments, WaveDriver), which were performed in $1 \mathrm{M}$ $\mathrm{KOH}$ aqueous solution. The reference and counter electrode is Mercury/Mercuric oxide $(\mathrm{Hg} / \mathrm{HgO}, 1 \mathrm{M} \mathrm{KOH})$ and platinum foil, respectively. The working electrode was a glassy carbon electrode $\left(0.196 \mathrm{~cm}^{-2}\right.$ ) coated with different catalyst samples. For sample preparation on rotating disk, $2.0 \mathrm{mg}$ catalyst was dispersed in a mixed solution (Nafion solution: $8 \mu \mathrm{L}$, deionized water: $192 \mu \mathrm{L}$, isopropanol: 100 $\mu \mathrm{L}$ ). The mixture was ultrasonicated for $1 \mathrm{~h}$ to obtain homogeneous dispersion. $10 \mu \mathrm{L}$ of the dispersion was coated on the polished $\mathrm{GC}$ electrode. The electrode was then dried and used for electrochemical studies. The rotating speed was set at $1600 \mathrm{rpm}$ to prevent $\mathrm{O}_{2}$ concentrate on the electrode surface. Before LSV test, the catalysts were first activated by $C V$ test $\left(1.0\right.$ to $1.7 \mathrm{~V}$ vs. RHE, $\left.10 \mathrm{mV} \mathrm{s}^{-1}\right)$ for 30 cycles. LSV polarization curves were acquired at $5 \mathrm{mV} \mathrm{s}^{-1}$ to illustrate the catalytic activity, corrected with $95 \%$ iR compensation. Chronopotentiometry measurement was performed at $10 \mathrm{~mA} \mathrm{~cm}{ }^{-2}$ to measure the stability performance. ElS was tested at $0.6 \mathrm{~V}(\mathrm{vs} . \mathrm{Hg} / \mathrm{HgO})$ with the frequency ranging from $0.1$ to $100 \mathrm{kHz}$. The ECSA was evaluated by calculated the $C_{D L}$ of the samples based on the $C V$ curves via Equ. (1). ${ }^{[17 \mathrm{~b}]}$ The potential window of $\mathrm{CV}$ was $0.3-0.4 \mathrm{~V}$ vs. $\mathrm{Hg} / \mathrm{HgO}$, and the scan rates were set at $10,20,50$, and $100 \mathrm{mV} \mathrm{s}^{-1}$.

\[
\frac{i_{a}-i_{b}}{2}=v \cdot \mathrm{C}_{\mathrm{DL}}
\]

By plotting $\Delta \mathrm{i}$ and scan rate, values of $\mathrm{C}_{\mathrm{DL}}$ can be determined by the slope. $i_{a}$ and $i_{c}$ are the currents at $0.35 \vee$ vs. $\mathrm{Hg} / \mathrm{HgO}, v$ is scan rate.

The TOF of the electrocatalysts were idetermined by Equ. (2) and (3).

\[
\mathrm{n}=\frac{\mathrm{m}_{\text {mass }}}{\mathrm{M}}
\]

\[
\mathrm{TOF}=\frac{J A}{4 \mathrm{Fn}}
\]

where $\mathrm{n}$ is the number of moles of the active sites (Ni) on the rotating disk electrode, $m_{\text {mass }}$ is mass loading of active materials and $M$ is molar mass of active materials, respectively. $J$ is the current density at overpotential of 300 and $350 \mathrm{mV}$ in $\mathrm{A} \mathrm{cm}^{-2}, \mathrm{~A}$ is the area of the rotating disk electrode $\left(0.196 \mathrm{~cm}^{-2}\right)$ and $\mathrm{F}$ is the Faraday constant $(96485 \mathrm{C} \mathrm{mol}$ ${ }^{1}$ ). The TOF was calculated assuming a $100 \%$ Faradic efficiency.

